Commit Message:
Implement configure.py to generate ninja build script

While nothing is containerized in Docker yet, this commit implements the
workflow that will run inside the container to build projects. You can
run it manually to check it out if you want, but it's a big pain.

You'll need:
    - An input project with a Hi-C file and workflow.yaml
      (calling it project.yaml instead is also acceptable)
    - The hic2structure.py script installed and available
      in your PATH
    - The Ninja build tool installed on your system
    - LAMMPS installed on your system (called 'lmp')
    - The 4DGB Browser repository cloned and checked-out
      somewhere on your system (along with gtk.min.js built
      and placed in the repo's server/static/gtk/js/ directory)

(This is all stuff that would normally be handled when the Docker
image is built)

From there, you can run the scripts/configure.py script with the
following arguments:

    scripts/configure.py path/to/project/directory path/to/output/directory path/to/4DGB/repo

After running that, switch the the output directory and run 'ninja' to build the
project. This will take a while since it needs to run the LAMMPS simulation.
Once done, just run 'python3 gtkserver.py' to launch a browser instance.

Implement containerized workflow

This is, for the most part, a copy of the functionality that's already
been implemented in the 4DGB Browser repository (with the plan being
to remove most of that functionality from the other repo).

The included Dockerfile gathers all the dependencies needed to build
a project from the input data, including cloning and building other
required repos.

The entrypoint script for the Docker image does most of the work
of actually building the project (using Ninja for incremental
builds) and then starting an instance of the browser.

With an image built, users only need to run the 'run_project' script
and provide it with the path to their project directory. This script
calls 'docker run' with all the appropriate arguments so that their
project will be built and made available to their web browser.
